  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Overstaying Your Visa</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Vietnam penalizes overstays strictly—fines, potential detention, and future visa difficulties. Track your dates carefully. Set calendar reminders. Your agent should help but ultimately it's your responsibility.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming Rules Won't Change</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Vietnam has changed visa policies multiple times. What works today may not work next year. Stay connected to expat communities for updates, and have backup plans if your visa situation changes.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Skipping Health Insurance</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Healthcare is cheap for basic care, but a serious illness at an international hospital can cost $20,000-50,000. Evacuation to Bangkok even more. Insurance costs $100-300/month—worth every dong.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Using Unreliable Visa Agents</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Cheap visa agents sometimes deliver poor service or even fake documents. Research thoroughly, use referrals from established expats, and pay for quality. A good agent is worth the extra cost.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Learning Basic Vietnamese</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Unlike Philippines or Malaysia, English is limited outside tourist areas. Basic Vietnamese dramatically improves daily life, relationships, and shows respect. Take lessons—it's challenging but rewarding.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Vietnam</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Vietnam's healthcare has improved dramatically, with international-standard private hospitals in major cities. However, quality varies significantly, and complex cases may require treatment abroad.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Major Hospitals</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>FV Hospital</strong> - HCMC, JCI-accredited, best in Vietnam</li>
      <li><strong>Vinmec</strong> - Multiple locations, growing chain, good quality</li>
      <li><strong>Family Medical Practice</strong> - HCMC, Hanoi, Da Nang, expat-focused</li>
      <li><strong>Hoan My</strong> - Multiple locations, affordable private</li>
      <li><strong>Columbia Asia</strong> - International chain, Saigon location</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Sample Costs (Private, Without Insurance)</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>GP visit:</strong> $30-60</li>
      <li><strong>Specialist:</strong> $50-100</li>
      <li><strong>MRI:</strong> $150-300</li>
      <li><strong>Dental cleaning:</strong> $20-40</li>
      <li><strong>Hospital room (private):</strong> $100-200/night</li>
      <li><strong>Evacuation to Bangkok:</strong> $10,000-30,000</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Medical tourism base:</strong> Many Vietnam expats use it as a base for medical tourism. Fly to Bangkok for major procedures (excellent hospitals, 2-hour flight), or Singapore for complex care. Your insurance should cover regional treatment.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is the business visa approach legal?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, having a business visa with a sponsor is legal. You're not working illegally—you simply have sponsorship that allows long-term stay. It's a widely used, accepted approach. The gray area is that you're not actually doing business, but this is common and tolerated.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Will Vietnam ever have a retirement visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          There have been discussions about implementing a retirement visa program similar to Thailand's. No firm timeline exists. For now, the workarounds described in this guide are the practical options.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How's the internet?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Vietnam has good internet infrastructure, especially in cities. Fiber is common in Da Nang, HCMC, Hanoi (50-100+ Mbps). Some websites are blocked (Facebook intermittently) but VPNs work. Good for remote work.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Vietnam safe?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Vietnam is generally very safe. Violent crime against foreigners is rare. Main concerns are petty theft (bag snatching), traffic accidents (scooter traffic is chaotic), and scams. Use normal precautions and you'll be fine.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Vietnamese?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          In expat-heavy areas, you can get by with English and translation apps. But Vietnamese is challenging (tonal language) and knowing basics dramatically improves life. Many expats learn enough for daily interactions.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about the weather?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Climate varies by region. South (HCMC) is hot year-round. Central (Da Nang) has rainy season October-February. North (Hanoi) has cool winters. Most expats prefer Da Nang's climate—warm but less extreme than the south.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Vietnam offers one of Asia's most affordable and culturally rich retirement experiences—if you're comfortable navigating a visa situation without a formal retirement program. The food is incredible, the people are warm, and your money goes incredibly far.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The tradeoffs are visa uncertainty (rules can change), healthcare limitations for complex cases (plan for evacuation), and a developing-country environment. But for adventurous retirees who embrace flexibility, Vietnam delivers an extraordinary quality of life at minimal cost.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Vietnam has no retirement visa, but thousands of retirees live there happily using business visa workarounds. It's best for flexible, adventurous retirees seeking ultra-low costs and cultural immersion. Get comprehensive health insurance, use a reputable visa agent, and embrace the ride. Da Nang and Hoi An are ideal starting points.
      </p>
